[## LECTURE 3.1 — VAULT DYNAMIC CREDENTIALS: NO MORE STATIC PASSWORDS]
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
CC6.1 is the single most commonly cited finding in SOC 2 audits.
Not because companies ignore access control.
They do not.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
The findings come from the gap between what engineers believe is true
and what is actually true.
Engineers believe their system has no static credentials.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
The auditor finds a hardcoded database password in a ConfigMap.
Engineers believe only the API team can access production secrets.
The auditor finds a developer service account with cluster dash admin.

4
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Engineers believe access is reviewed quarterly.
The auditor asks for the last review.
And finds none was ever conducted.

5
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Static credentials have four properties that auditors hate.
They do not expire.
They grant excessive privilege.

6
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
They require downtime to rotate.
And they are shared across multiple replicas.

7
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Vault's Database Secrets Engine solves all four problems.
Every pod gets a unique credential with a defined TTL.
The credential is scoped to exactly the permissions the pod needs.

8
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Rotation is automatic and zero-downtime.
The audit log distinguishes connections by Vault lease ID.

9
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Let me show you how to configure Vault dynamic credentials for RDS.

10
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
First, verify that Vault is running and unsealed.
kubectl exec minus n vault vault-0 dash dash vault status.
The sealed field should be false.

11
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Enable the database secrets engine.
kubectl exec minus n vault vault-0 dash dash vault secrets enable database.

12
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Create a dedicated Vault admin user in PostgreSQL.
Never use a superuser account for Vault.
Create a user named vaultadmin with CREATEROLE privilege.

13
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Grant SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE on all tables in the public schema.
This user can create and drop roles but cannot access customer data directly.

14
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Now configure Vault to connect to RDS.
Get the RDS host endpoint using aws rds describe-db-instances.

15
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Run vault write database forward slash config forward slash financial-rag.
Set plugin_name to postgresql-database-plugin.
Set allowed_roles to rag-app, rag-readonly, and rag-agent.

16
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
The connection URL includes sslmode equals verify-full.
And sslrootcert points to the RDS CA bundle.
This enforces TLS for the database connection.

17
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Now create the roles.
First, the rag-app role for API pods.
Set db_name to financial-rag.

18
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
The creation_statements are SQL that Vault executes.
CREATE ROLE with a random name and password, VALID UNTIL the expiration time.
Then GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE on all tables.

19
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
GRANT USAGE on the public schema.
And GRANT USAGE, SELECT on all sequences.
Finally, set default TTL to one hour and max TTL to twenty-four hours.

20
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Create a read-only role for reporting.
It only gets SELECT permission on tables.
No INSERT, no UPDATE.

21
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Create an agent role for worker pods.
It gets SELECT on financial_chunks and sec_filings.
And SELECT, INSERT only on analysis_history.

22
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Test the configuration.
Run vault read database forward slash creds forward slash rag-app.
The output shows lease_id, lease_duration of one hour, password, and username.

23
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
The username follows the pattern v dash k8s dash rag-app dash random characters.
Verify the role exists in PostgreSQL.
Run SELECT rolname, rolvaliduntil FROM pg_roles.

24
00:11:30,000 --> 00:12:00,000
The rolvaliduntil field should show the expiration time one hour from now.
After one hour, Vault automatically runs DROP ROLE.

25
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Now we need to inject these credentials into our pods.
This is done with the Vault Agent sidecar.

26
00:12:30,000 --> 00:13:00,000
In the API deployment YAML, add annotations.
vault.hashicorp.com forward slash agent-inject equals true.
vault.hashicorp.com forward slash role equals financial-rag-api.

27
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:30,000
vault.hashicorp.com forward slash agent-inject-secret-db-creds
equals database forward slash creds forward slash rag-app.

28
00:13:30,000 --> 00:14:00,000
The template renders the secret as export statements.
POSTGRES_USER equals the username.
POSTGRES_PASSWORD equals the password.

29
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:30,000
When the pod starts, Vault Agent injects a sidecar container.
It fetches the credentials and writes them to forward slash vault forward slash secrets.
The volume is a tmpfs in-memory mount, never written to disk.

30
00:14:30,000 --> 00:15:00,000
The application reads the credentials from this file at startup.
The credentials are never in environment variables.
Which could be leaked in logs or crash dumps.

31
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:30,000
The renewal annotation sends a SIGHUP signal to the application.
This triggers the application to re-read the credential file.
Zero-downtime credential rotation.

32
00:15:30,000 --> 00:16:00,000
Your lab exercise is to configure the Vault database secrets engine.
Create the three roles with appropriate permissions.
Test generating credentials manually.

33
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:30,000
Verify that after one hour, the credential no longer works.
Deploy the Vault Agent sidecar injection.
Confirm the pod receives dynamic credentials.

34
00:16:30,000 --> 00:17:00,000
This is one of the most impactful security improvements you can make.
Auditors love dynamic credentials because they eliminate long-lived secrets.

35
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:30,000
In the next lecture, we will configure Vault policies.
And implement IAM least privilege with EKS Pod Identity.

