[## LECTURE 3.2 — VAULT POLICIES AND IAM LEAST PRIVILEGE]

36
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Vault dynamic credentials eliminate static passwords.
But Vault itself needs access control.
Which service accounts can read which secrets?

37
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Vault policies define this.
Each service account gets a policy that grants read access
to exactly the secrets it needs and nothing else.

38
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
First, enable Kubernetes authentication in Vault.
vault auth enable kubernetes.

39
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Configure it with your cluster's host, CA certificate, and token reviewer JWT.
The token reviewer JWT is created with kubectl create token.
It must have a long duration because Vault uses it to validate service account tokens.

40
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Now write Vault policies.
The API service policy grants read access to database forward slash creds forward slash rag-app.
Read access to secret forward slash data forward slash financial-rag forward slash openai.
And read access to secret forward slash data forward slash financial-rag forward slash field-encryption-key.

41
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Notice the policy explicitly does not grant list or create capabilities.
The service account cannot list all available secrets.
It can only read the specific paths it needs.

42
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
The agent service policy is narrower.
It can read database forward slash creds forward slash rag-agent instead of rag-app.
This role has fewer database permissions.

43
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The ingestion service policy has no LLM access at all.
Only database credentials and possibly AWS credentials if not using IRSA.

44
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Now bind Kubernetes service accounts to these policies.
vault write auth forward slash kubernetes forward slash role forward slash financial-rag-api.
bound_service_account_names equals financial-rag-api.
bound_service_account_namespaces equals financial-rag.

45
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
policies equals financial-rag-api.
ttl equals one hour.

46
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Test that the API service account cannot access agent secrets.
Create a token with the financial-rag-api policy.
Try to read database forward slash creds forward slash rag-agent.
You should get a permission denied error.

47
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Now let us move to IAM least privilege for AWS access.
Your pods need to read from S3, write to CloudWatch, and describe RDS instances.
But they do not need to create EC2 instances or modify IAM roles.

48
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Create an IAM policy document for the API service.
First statement: S3ReadEmbeddings.
Effect Allow. Actions s3:GetObject and s3:ListBucket.

49
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Resources are scoped to the embeddings bucket.
And only the forward slash vectors forward slash prefix.
This prevents reading backup files or other buckets.

50
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Second statement: CloudWatchLogs.
Actions logs:CreateLogStream and logs:PutLogEvents.
Resource scoped to forward slash financial-rag forward slash asterisk.

51
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Third statement: RDSDescribeOnly.
Action rds:DescribeDBInstances.
Resource is the specific production RDS instance ARN.

52
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Fourth statement: KMSDecryptViaS3.
Actions kms:Decrypt and kms:DescribeKey.
Condition requires kms:ViaService equals s3 dot region dot amazonaws dot com.

53
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
This means the API pod can only decrypt KMS keys
when the request comes from S3.
It cannot decrypt arbitrary ciphertext.

54
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Finally, an explicit deny statement for dangerous actions.
iam colon asterisk, ec2 colon asterisk, rds:Create asterisk.
s3:Delete asterisk, kms:Delete asterisk.

55
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
This is belt and suspenders defense in depth.
Even if a later policy accidentally grants something broad,
the explicit deny blocks it.

56
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Attach this policy to an IAM role.
Create an EKS Pod Identity association.
This binds the Kubernetes service account to the IAM role.

57
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Now test the permissions.
Assume the role using aws sts assume-role.
Export the temporary credentials.

58
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Test allowed actions.
aws s3 ls on the vectors prefix should succeed.
aws rds describe-db-instances should succeed.

59
00:11:30,000 --> 00:12:00,000
Test denied actions.
aws s3 ls on the backups prefix should fail with AccessDenied.
aws iam list-roles should fail.
aws ec2 describe-instances should fail.

60
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Your lab exercise is to create the Vault policies.
Bind them to the service accounts.
Test that each service account can only access its intended secrets.

61
00:12:30,000 --> 00:13:00,000
Create the IAM least privilege policy.
Attach it via EKS Pod Identity.
Test that allowed actions work and disallowed actions fail.

62
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:30,000
Document the permission boundary for your auditor.
In the next lecture, we will configure Kubernetes RBAC.
And enforce namespace isolation.

