[## LECTURE 3.3 — KUBERNETES RBAC: NAMESPACE ISOLATION]

63
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
By default, every pod in a Kubernetes cluster
can call the Kubernetes API server using its service account token.
The default service account may have no explicit permissions.

64
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
But in older or misconfigured clusters,
it may have inherited broad permissions through a ClusterRoleBinding.
RBAC prevents this by explicitly defining what each service account can do.

65
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Create service accounts for each workload.
api-service, agent, ingestion.
Each gets its own service account.

66
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
For EKS, also annotate with the IAM role ARN.
eks.amazonaws.com forward slash role-arn points to the IAM role we created.
This integrates AWS IAM with Kubernetes service accounts.

67
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Now create a Role for the API service account.
This Role is namespace-scoped. It cannot affect other namespaces.

68
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
The API service account needs to read its own ConfigMap for feature flags.
It needs to read its own Service for self-discovery.
That is it.

69
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
It cannot read secrets.
It cannot create or update anything.
It cannot list pods in its own namespace.
It cannot exec into pods.

70
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Bind the Role to the service account with a RoleBinding.
roleRef points to the Role we created.
subjects lists the service account.

71
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Create a similar Role and RoleBinding for the agent service account.
It has slightly broader permissions.
It needs to read HPA metrics and its own ConfigMap.

72
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Apply the RBAC configuration.
kubectl apply dash f.

73
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Now test that the API service account cannot do things it should not.
kubectl auth can-i get secrets dash dash as equals the service account.
Expected output: no.

74
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
kubectl auth can-i list pods in the financial-rag namespace.
Expected output: no.
kubectl auth can-i get secrets in the kube-system namespace.
Expected output: no.

75
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Test that it can do what it needs.
kubectl auth can-i get configmaps in the financial-rag namespace.
Expected output: yes.

76
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Now enforce Pod Security Standards on the namespace.
kubectl label namespace financial-rag.
pod-security.kubernetes.io forward slash enforce equals restricted.

77
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
This enforces: no root user, no privileged containers,
read-only root filesystem, all capabilities dropped,
and seccomp profile set to runtime default.

78
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Verify the label is applied.
kubectl get namespace financial-rag dash o jsonpath equals dot metadata dot labels.

79
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Save the RBAC configuration as evidence.
kubectl get roles, rolebindings, serviceaccounts minus n financial-rag dash o yaml.
Output to soc2-evidence under today's date in CC6.1.
Call it rbac-configs dot yaml.

80
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Your lab exercise is to create the RBAC roles and bindings.
Test each service account with kubectl auth can-i.
Confirm that the API service account cannot read secrets or list pods.

81
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Apply the Pod Security Standard to the namespace.
Verify that a pod running as root would be rejected.
In the next lecture, we will implement API key lifecycle management.

