[## LECTURE 3.4 — API KEY LIFECYCLE: GENERATION, ROTATION, AND REVOCATION]

82
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Your customers use API keys to authenticate to your service.
These keys need lifecycle management too.
Creation, rotation, and revocation.

83
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Auditors ask three questions.
How long are API keys valid?
How do you revoke them when an employee leaves?
How do customers know when to rotate?

84
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Let me show you a complete API key management system.
First, the database model.
Never store raw keys. Store only the SHA-256 hash.

85
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
The table includes id, key_hash, name, created_by, created_at.
expires_at, last_used_at, is_active.
revoked_at, revoked_by, revocation_reason.
And rotation_of to track which key this replaced.

86
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
The default TTL is ninety days.
Why ninety days? Industry best practice.
Short enough to limit exposure if a key leaks.
Long enough that customers are not annoyed by frequent rotation.

87
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
The generate method creates a raw key using secrets.token_urlsafe.
Thirty-two bytes of randomness, base64 encoded.
Prefix it with finrag underscore for easy detection in secret scanning.

88
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Compute the SHA-256 hash of the raw key.
Store the hash, not the raw key.
Insert a record with expires_at equals now plus ninety days.

89
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Return both the database record and the raw key string.
The raw key is shown to the customer exactly once.
It cannot be recovered later.

90
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
The validate method is called on every API request.
Check that the key starts with the finrag prefix.
Compute the hash of the raw key.

91
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Query for a matching key that is active and not expired.
If found, update last_used_at to now.
Return the record.

92
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
The revoke method immediately deactivates a key.
Set is_active to false.
Set revoked_at, revoked_by, and revocation_reason.
Commit the change.

93
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Revocation takes effect on the next request.
No grace period.
No exceptions.

94
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
The rotate method creates a new key.
And marks the old key for deactivation.
The old key remains valid for twenty-four hours.
This allows in-flight requests to complete.

95
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
After twenty-four hours, the old key expires.
The new key has a fresh ninety-day TTL.

96
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
The get_expiring_soon method returns keys expiring within fourteen days.
This is used by a daily CronJob to notify customers.
Send an email: your API key expires in N days.

97
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
The get_unused method returns keys not used in ninety days.
These are candidates for automatic revocation.
You can choose to revoke them or contact the customer.

98
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Create a CronJob that runs every Monday at 9 AM.
It queries for expiring keys and sends notifications.
It also logs unused keys for the compliance team.

99
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
The CronJob uses the API service account.
It runs a Python script that imports APIKeyManager.
It sends emails via your email provider or Slack.

100
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Collect evidence for the auditor.
cat docs forward slash api-key-policy dot md.
Should show ninety-day TTL and thirty-day rotation notice.

101
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Show active keys and their expiry dates.
kubectl exec into the API pod and run psql.
SELECT name, created_by, expires_at, last_used_at FROM api_keys.

102
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Show rotation logs.
kubectl logs minus n financial-rag job forward slash api-key-rotation-xxx.
Grep for api_key dot rotated.

103
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Your lab exercise is to implement the API key manager.
Create keys with ninety-day expiry.
Verify that expired keys are rejected.

104
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Test immediate revocation.
Schedule the rotation CronJob.
Document the rotation schedule for your auditor.

105
00:11:30,000 --> 00:12:00,000
In the next lecture, we will encrypt Kubernetes secrets at rest.
etcd encryption for CC6.6.

