[## LECTURE 3.5 — ETCD ENCRYPTION: PROTECTING KUBERNETES SECRETS AT REST]

106
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Every Kubernetes Secret is stored in etcd.
By default, Kubernetes stores secrets as base64-encoded values.
Not encrypted.

107
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Anyone with etcd access can run etcdctl get
forward slash registry forward slash secrets forward slash financial-rag forward slash vault-token.
And read the secret in plaintext.

108
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
For SOC 2 CC6.6 to cover Kubernetes secrets,
etcd must be encrypted.
For EKS, this is enabled at the cluster level via a KMS key.

109
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Create a KMS key for etcd secrets encryption.
aws kms create-key with description EKS etcd secrets encryption.
Tags include Control equals CC6.6.

110
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Create an alias for the key.
aws kms create-alias dash dash alias-name alias forward slash financial-rag-etcd.
Enable key rotation on the key.

111
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Now enable etcd encryption on the EKS cluster.
aws eks update-cluster-config dash dash name financial-rag-prod.
encryption-config with resources set to secrets.
Provider keyArn set to the KMS key ARN.

112
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Wait for the update to complete.
This takes five to ten minutes.
aws eks wait cluster-active dash dash name financial-rag-prod.

113
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Verify the encryption configuration.
aws eks describe-cluster dash dash name financial-rag-prod.
Query cluster.encryptionConfig.

114
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
The output should show an array with resources equals secrets.
And provider dot keyArn equals your KMS key ARN.

115
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Create a test secret.
kubectl create secret generic test-secret.
from-literal password equals super-secret-value.

116
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Get the secret.
kubectl get secret test-secret dash o yaml.
The data field should show encrypted content.
Not base64 of the original value.

117
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
For self-managed Kubernetes, you need to configure the API server directly.
Create an encryption-configuration YAML file.
resources colon secrets. providers colon aescbc with a base64-encoded key.

118
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Then modify the kube-apiserver manifest.
Add dash dash encryption-provider-config equals forward slash etc forward slash kubernetes forward slash encryption-config dot yaml.

119
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Save evidence for the auditor.
aws eks describe-cluster dash dash name financial-rag-prod.
Query cluster.encryptionConfig.
Save the output to etcd-encryption dot json.

120
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Verify no unencrypted secrets remain.
kubectl get secrets dash dash all-namespaces dash o json.
Check each secret for encryption configuration annotations.

121
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Your lab exercise is to enable etcd encryption for your EKS cluster.
Create the KMS key and enable rotation.
Apply the cluster update and verify the configuration.

122
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Create a test secret and verify it is encrypted at rest.
Save the evidence.
In the next lecture, we will implement access logging.
And the complete audit trail.

