[## LECTURE 3.6 — ACCESS LOGGING AND THE COMPLETE AUDIT TRAIL]

123
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
CC6.1 requires that access be restricted.
CC7.2 requires that access be logged.
Together they mean every successful and failed access attempt
must generate a log entry.

124
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
The log must answer who accessed what, when, and from where.
For the financial RAG agent, this means five things.
Every API request logged with key prefix, path, status, and latency.

125
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Every Vault credential issuance logged with lease ID and role.
Every Kubernetes API call logged via EKS audit logs.
Every database connection logged via pgAudit.
Every failed authentication logged immediately with client IP.

126
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Let me show you the audit logger implementation.
Create a class AuditLogger with static methods.

127
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
The api_request method logs every API request.
Fields include timestamp, request_id, method, path, client_ip.
api_key_prefix, status_code, latency_ms, and user_agent.

128
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Notice we log only the key prefix. The first eight characters.
Never the full key.
The prefix is enough to correlate logs without exposing the secret.

129
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
The auth_failure method logs authentication failures.
Fields include reason, client_ip, path, and api_key_prefix if available.
This is a warning-level log, not info.

130
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The permission_denied method logs authorization failures.
Even if the API key is valid, the user may not have permission for the action.
These should be rare and investigated.

131
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
The key_event method logs API key lifecycle events.
Generated, revoked, rotated, or expired.
Includes key_id, actor, and reason.

132
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Now integrate the audit logger into the API middleware.
In the APIKeyMiddleware, generate a request_id at the start.
Use uuid dot uuid4 dot hex.

133
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Store the request_id in the request state.
This makes it available to other middleware and handlers.
For correlation across logs.

134
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
If the request is to a public path like health or metrics,
bypass authentication but still log at a lower level.
Do not log the request body.

135
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
If the API key is missing or invalid,
call AuditLogger dot auth_failure.
Then raise an HTTP 401 or 403.

136
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
If the key is valid, store the key record in the request state.
Proceed to the handler.
After the handler returns, calculate latency.

137
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Call AuditLogger dot api_request with all the fields.
This logs every successful and failed request.
The success field is derived from status code two hundred to four hundred.

138
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Now enable Kubernetes API audit logging.
For EKS, run aws eks update-cluster-config.
Set logging clusterLogging types to api, audit, authenticator, controllerManager, scheduler.
Enabled equals true.

139
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Verify logs are flowing to CloudWatch.
aws logs tail forward slash aws forward slash eks forward slash financial-rag-prod forward slash cluster.
Filter pattern audit.

140
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Query for secret access attempts in the last twenty-four hours.
aws logs filter-log-events with filter pattern secrets and get.
Extract the user, resource name, and timestamp.

141
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
This shows you exactly who accessed which secrets.
A powerful audit capability for your incident response runbook.

142
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Your lab exercise is to implement the audit logger.
Integrate it into the API middleware.
Test that every request produces a structured log entry.

143
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Enable EKS audit logging.
Query the logs and confirm you can see API access events.
Save a sample query output as evidence.

144
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
In the next lecture, we will automate the quarterly access review.
This closes the final CC6.1 gap.

