[## LECTURE 3.7 — QUARTERLY ACCESS REVIEW: AUTOMATED EVIDENCE]

145
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Quarterly access reviews are the most commonly cited CC6.3 gap.
Not because companies do not conduct them.
The problem is documentation.

146
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
An auditor asks: show me the Q1 2026 access review.
The answer should be a signed document listing all active API keys.
IAM roles, and Kubernetes service accounts.

147
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
With a certification that each is still needed.
Instead, the answer is: we discussed it in a Slack channel.
That is not evidence.

148
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Automated reviews solve this.
A CronJob runs quarterly, generates the report,
uploads it to the immutable evidence bucket,
and posts a certification request to Slack.

149
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Let me show you the access review script.

150
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
First, set the date and reviewer.
REVIEWER defaults to git config user dot email.
REPORT_FILE points to soc2-evidence forward slash access-reviews forward slash access-review-dash date dot md.

151
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
The report has four sections.
API keys, IAM roles, Kubernetes service accounts,
and unused access older than ninety days.

152
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
For API keys, query the database for active keys.
Show ID prefix, name, created_by, created date, expiry date, last used date.
Mark keys that have never been used as REVOKE question mark.

153
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
For IAM roles, list roles that contain financial-rag in the name.
Show role name, creation date, last used date, and attached policies.
Mark any role that has not been used in ninety days.

154
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
For Kubernetes service accounts, list all service accounts in the financial-rag namespace.
Show namespace, service account name, creation timestamp, and bound roles.
The bound roles section requires manual inspection.

155
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
For unused access, query API keys with last_used_at older than ninety days.
Or last_used_at is null.
These are candidates for revocation.

156
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
The report ends with a certification section.
The reviewer signs off that all listed access is still required.
And that any access marked REVOKE has been actioned.

157
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Schedule this report as a quarterly CronJob.
Schedule zero nine one one, four, seven, ten asterisk.
This runs at 9 AM on the first day of January, April, July, and October.

158
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
The CronJob uses the compliance-runner service account.
It runs the access-review dot sh script.
Then uploads the report to S3.

159
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
After the report is generated, a separate webhook posts it to a Slack channel.
The compliance lead reviews the report and clicks approve.
The approval action is logged in the same channel.

160
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
The completed report and the Slack approval message together form the evidence.
The report proves what was reviewed.
The Slack message proves who approved it and when.

161
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Run the script manually before your audit.
Review the report for any REVOKE question mark items.
Revoke any unused keys with kubectl exec psql.

162
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Save the signed report to the evidence bucket.
Upload it with aws s3 cp.
Send the approval request to your compliance team.

163
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Your lab exercise is to run the access review script.
Review the generated report.
Revoke any unused API keys.

164
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Save the report to the evidence bucket.
Simulate the approval process.
Document the review for your auditor.

165
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
In the final lecture of Phase 3, we will recap what your auditor will test.
And prepare for Phase 4: Immutable Audit Logging.

