[## LECTURE 3.8 — PHASE 3 RECAP: WHAT YOUR AUDITOR WILL TEST]

166
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
By the end of Phase 3, you have eliminated static credentials.
Every database password is dynamic, short-lived, and audited.
Your pods authenticate to Vault using Kubernetes service account tokens.

167
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
IAM roles are scoped to exactly what each service needs.
No wildcard permissions. No overprivileged roles.
Explicit deny statements block dangerous actions.

168
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Kubernetes RBAC prevents namespace escape.
The API service account cannot read secrets or list pods.
Pod Security Standards enforce restricted mode.

169
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
API keys have a ninety-day TTL with automated rotation notifications.
Revocation is immediate. No grace period.
Unused keys are flagged for review.

170
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
etcd encryption protects Kubernetes secrets at rest.
Even if someone gains access to the etcd storage,
the secrets are unreadable without the KMS key.

171
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Every access attempt is logged with a unique request ID.
Failed authentications generate warning-level logs.
API key lifecycle events are tracked with actor and reason.

172
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Quarterly access reviews are automated and documented.
The evidence bucket contains signed review reports.
Each report shows exactly which access was reviewed and approved.

173
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Here is what your auditor will test for CC6.1.
First, no static database passwords.
They will ask to see how the API pod authenticates to PostgreSQL.

174
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Your answer is Vault dynamic credentials.
Show them forward slash vault forward slash secrets forward slash db-creds exists in the running pod.
And the username matches the pattern v dash k8s dash rag-app dash random.

175
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Second, least privilege IAM.
They will ask what permissions the API pod has in AWS.
Show them the IAM policy document.
It grants specific S3 prefixes and specific CloudWatch log groups.

176
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Third, RBAC namespace isolation.
They will run kubectl auth can-i tests against your service accounts.
Confirm that the API service account cannot read secrets or list pods.

177
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Fourth, API key rotation.
They will ask how often keys are rotated and how revocation works.
Answer: ninety-day TTL enforced by the database constraint on expires_at.
Immediate revocation via the is_active equals false flag.

178
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Fifth, access reviews.
They will ask for the last three quarterly review reports.
Show them three Markdown files in the evidence bucket.
Each with timestamps, reviewer names, and any revocation actions taken.

179
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
What is ready for your auditor.
No static database credentials anywhere.
Every IAM role has least privilege documented.

180
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
RBAC prevents namespace escape.
API keys rotate every ninety days.
etcd encryption verified.
Service account tokens expire.

181
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Every access is logged.
Quarterly reviews prove ongoing compliance.
This is the foundation for CC6.1.

182
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
In Phase 4, we will build the immutable audit logging system.
The analysis_history table will become append-only.
With hash chaining and digital signatures for tamper detection.

183
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
CloudWatch logs will have seven-year retention with KMS encryption.
S3 Object Lock in COMPLIANCE mode will make archives immutable.
pgAudit will log every database operation.

184
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
And monthly audit reports will be generated automatically.
With integrity verification of the entire hash chain.

185
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Continue to Phase 4 when you are ready.

